        "description": "h2. Background\n\nPhase 1 rebooks onto the *next available direct flight* on the same origin/destination within a search window. Real networks often require *multi-hop* recovery (e.g., SFO→DEN→JFK) when nonstop capacity is gone.\n\nh2. Acceptance criteria\n\n# *Model / data*\n#* Introduce an explicit representation of a *passenger itinerary* (single- or multi-segment) without breaking existing {{Booking}} rows (migration strategy documented in PR).\n#* A booking references either a *single segment* (Phase 1 compatible) or belongs to an itinerary group.\n# *Search*\n#* Given a disrupted segment, the rebooking engine can propose *valid multi-hop paths* constrained by:\n#** Minimum connection time between legs (configurable via env, e.g. {{MIN_CONNECTION_MINUTES}}).\n#** Maximum additional travel time vs original itinerary (configurable).\n#** Airport compatibility (same metro exceptions configurable; default strict).\n# *Algorithm*\n#* VIP > BUSINESS > ECONOMY ordering is preserved *within* each disruption batch.\n#* If *no* valid path exists, passenger booking ends in {{NO_SEAT_AVAILABLE}} (or itinerary-level equivalent) and downstream compensation/notifications still run deterministically.\n# *Correctness*\n#* Unit tests cover at least:\n#** 2-hop successful rebook\n#** Impossible connection → {{NO_SEAT_AVAILABLE}}\n#** Priority ordering with mixed loyalty on the same disrupted flight\n# *Operational*\n#* Structured logs include {{itineraryId}}, {{path}}, and {{correlationId}} for each rebook decision.\n\nh2. Non-goals (for this ticket)\n\n* Global optimization across the entire network (that is a separate research spike).\n\nh2. Definition of done\n\n* Migrations applied, tests green, README section updated for new env vars and behavior.",
